The bigger problem

The real problem is not “making games faster.”

The real problem is:

We do not have an easy way to generate, test, evaluate, and train agents inside rich 3D environments.

Game studios need this for:

AI playtesting
level balancing
NPC behavior testing
procedural world validation
game mechanics tuning
physics/collision bug discovery

Robotics and physical-AI teams need this for:

synthetic training environments
robot navigation tasks
manipulation tasks
domain randomization
sim-to-real preparation
reward design
embodied agent evaluation

NVIDIA Isaac Sim is already positioned for robotics simulation, testing, and synthetic data generation, while Isaac Lab is a modular robot-learning framework for reinforcement learning, imitation learning, and motion planning.

So you should not compete head-on with Isaac, Unity, or Unreal. You should build the missing layer above them:

Prompt → 3D world → task/reward/sensors/actions → agent training/testing → export to engines/simulators.

That is the company.

