The core architecture

Think of your platform as a compiler.

1. Prompt layer

User describes a world:

Build a warehouse robot task where a wheeled robot must navigate around shelves, avoid workers, pick up a box, and deliver it to a loading bay.

The AI should not directly write random game code. It should convert the prompt into a structured intermediate representation.

2. WorldSpec layer

This is your most important product asset.

WorldSpec {
  scene: SceneSpec;
  entities: EntitySpec[];
  physics: PhysicsSpec;
  agents: AgentSpec[];
  tasks: TaskSpec[];
  sensors: SensorSpec[];
  actions: ActionSpec[];
  rewards: RewardSpec[];
  resets: ResetSpec[];
  randomization: DomainRandomizationSpec;
  metrics: EvaluationSpec;
}

This becomes your moat.

Other tools may generate assets. Your tool generates worlds that agents can understand and train inside.

3. Runtime layer

You need multiple runtimes over time, but start narrow.

First runtime:

Browser/WebGPU runtime using EXTRAVERSE.

Later runtimes:

Unity adapter
Unreal adapter
Isaac Sim / Isaac Lab adapter
Gymnasium-style RL adapter
USD/glTF export

Unity and Unreal are already building AI editor automation paths, including Unity AI tools and Unreal MCP. That means your product should integrate with them, not pretend they do not exist.

4. Agent evaluation layer

This is the magic.

Agents should be able to:

explore the generated world
attempt objectives
find broken paths
detect impossible tasks
measure difficulty
report bugs
suggest world changes
improve level layout
optimize reward functions

For games, this becomes AI playtesting.

For robotics, this becomes environment/task generation for policy training.

5. Training/export layer

For serious physical AI, do not try to run all RL training in the browser.

The browser is your demo and design surface.

Training should export to heavier systems like Isaac Lab, which is designed for robot learning workflows and high-performance simulation.

Your role:

Make environment creation 10x easier, then hand off training to the right backend.

