MVP plan
Month 1: Build the environment schema

Your first job is not graphics. It is the WorldSpec + TaskSpec.

Build:

WorldSpec
EntitySpec
AgentSpec
SensorSpec
ActionSpec
RewardSpec
ResetSpec
MetricSpec
RandomizationSpec

Example:

AgentSpec {
  id: "drone_01";
  embodiment: "quadrotor";
  sensors: ["rgb_camera", "depth", "imu", "position"];
  actions: {
    type: "continuous";
    values: ["throttle", "pitch", "roll", "yaw"];
  };
}

Reward example:

RewardSpec {
  success: "+100 if beacon delivered";
  shaping: "+1 for progress toward target";
  penalty: "-10 for collision";
  penaltyTime: "-0.01 per second";
}

This schema is the brain of the company.

Month 2: Build 3 generated environments

Build only three, but make them beautiful and functional.

Environment 1: Drone canyon
drone starts at base
must fly through rings
avoid terrain
land on pad
reward based on progress, time, collisions
Environment 2: Rover exploration
rover explores alien terrain
must find samples
avoid cliffs
return to base
Environment 3: Game level playtest
third-person character
collect objective
enemies or hazards
exit gate
AI agent tests if level is beatable

These three cover your full thesis.

Month 3: Build the agent evaluation system

At first, do not train deep RL from scratch.

Start with:

scripted baseline agents
pathfinding agents
heuristic agents
LLM planner + low-level controller
simple RL only where useful

Why? Because full RL training is slow and can distract you.

Your early product should prove:

“The agent can test and evaluate worlds.”

Then later:

“The agent can train policies.”

Month 4: Add RL interface

Create a clean API:

import extraverse

env = extraverse.load("drone_canyon_v1")
obs = env.reset(seed=42)

while True:
    action = policy(obs)
    obs, reward, done, info = env.step(action)
    if done:
        break

Support:

observations
actions
rewards
resets
domain randomization
success metrics
replay logs
Month 5: Export to Isaac Lab or Unity

Pick one serious export target first.

